Source: News briefs [edited]

[A] Indonesia, Philippines and Malaysian cruise ship crew from the
Washington Post:
<http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A9859-2003Apr11.html>
Indonesia and the Philippines reported their first cases of severe acute
respiratory syndrome, bringing to 20 the number of nations that have
reported SARS cases.
A Malaysian cruise ship, the Superstar Virgo, was also hit with SARS. One
crew member is ill and another is showing symptoms, a Star Cruises
spokeswoman said Friday. They have been admitted to hospitals in Singapore
and Malaysia.
[B] China, Beijing from The Daily Telegraph
<http://www.dailytelegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2003/04/12/wsars12.xml&sSheet=/news/2003/04/12/ixworld.html>
The Chinese government says that in Beijing there have been only 22 cases
of the fatal pneumonia that is spreading around the world, and 4 deaths.
[C] China, Shanghai from Asia Reuters
<http://asia.reuters.com/newsArticle.jhtml?type=scienceNews&storyID=2550165>
9 foreigners were in Shanghai hospitals on Friday with SARS symptoms
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There have been 109 new cases of SARS reported to WHO since the last
update on 10 Apr 2003, for a cumulative total case count of 2890. Among
these there have been 116 deaths (case fatality rate 4 percent) and 1373
have recovered (47.5 percent). The largest increase was in Hong Kong, with
61 new cases since the last update on 10 Apr 2003. The Taiwan Center for
Disease Control has reported 2 more probable cases in their update for
today than are included in the WHO daily update.
China reported 19 new cases since the last update on 10 Apr 2003. The
newswires have carried multiple reports suggesting underreporting of cases
from China. In the briefs section above [5], there are reports of 22 cases
currently being treated in Beijing according to official sources, whereas
in Shanghai there are reports of 9 non-Chinese nationals currently being
treated for SARS. In a press briefing held at WHO today, the last remark
of Dr. Heymann with respect to the outbreak in China was "And our team
thinks that there is disease in most provinces." We await further
information from the investigations of the WHO teams in China.
<http://www.who.int/csr/sars/Press_2003_04_11/en/>
In the Health Canada update [4], the addition of guidelines for blood banks
and securing the blood supply on the chance that SARS infections may be
associated with significant viremia and thereby transmissible via blood
transfusions is the first official announcement addressing this issue that
we have come across. After the experience in the USA during 2002 with
transmission of West Nile virus infections via blood transfusions, this is
a prudent public health measure until such time that significant viremia
has been ruled out.
Of interest is a new website on SARS developed by the Ministry of Health of
Singapore:
<http://app.moh.gov.sg/sar/sar01.asp>
The European Union, the United States, and Singapore did not post updates
on their respective SARS websites today (as of 9 PM EDST). We await further
word on whether there has been local transmission of SARS in the United
States (in yesterday's update there was information on a suspected contact
case in a work colleague). - Mod.MPP]
